  • 8/30/22, 11:32 PM
    Commented on #24 feat: add cargo-make to the docker image from harrison-ai/dataeng-tooling-rust

    @rfk , franklin-ai is setting up new repos at the moment, and this image and the dataeng-handbook in general are ideal for the most part. However we'd like to be using cargo-make instead of make for our new projects, due to

    • its make rules being in TOML format instead of the rather obscure Makefile syntax, and
    • it provides a lot of rust specific rules built-in, and can import third-party rulesets such as https://github.com/kazuk/cargo-make-coverage-grcov/blob/main/coverage_grcov.makefile.toml , all which results in commonality across rust projects reducing mental load when switching repos

    I used in my last Rust job to perform tasks that included building Rust and Python bits and pulling them together into a single exe installer on three platforms. Some steps might have been better optimised if we were using make instead, but only if we were using a lot of advanced Makefile syntax that are "write-and-forget-how-it-works" for all but the make gurus.

    It is a bit hard to determine how widespread its use is, but https://crates.io/crates/cargo-make 533k downloads is a good indicator.

    Also possibly going to be used in rust-lang c.f. https://github.com/rust-lang/rustc_codegen_gcc/blame/b4626b3ca07c4fcdce1d96840567005e294e5ecc/test.sh#L3

  • 8/27/22, 1:35 AM
    Commented on #654 Add tests to sdist from browniebroke/django-codemod

    Regarding why, I am a maintainer of the django package collection on openSUSE, and I frequently use codemod to fixup packages which havent done a release of the compatibility needed for the latest release of Django.

    e.g. https://build.opensuse.org/package/show/devel:languages:python:django/python-django-user-agents https://build.opensuse.org/package/view_file/devel:languages:python:django/python-django-user-agents/python-django-user-agents.spec?expand=1 is where you can see the tool being used. Packages get deleted on openSUSE if they fail to build for six weeks, so the clock is ticking. As soon as another Django release occurs, approx 20 django packages break. Your tool means I don't need to disable newly failing tests, or apply lots of patches against the most recent released version of a package, etc. Much appreciated.

    https://pypi.org/project/django-codemod/#files shows that there are wheels and sdists being uploaded. The wheels do not include tests, and are intended for normal pip usage. The wheels are downloaded by default by pip, and include only what is necessary to run the code. The sdist (source distribution) is where the tests reside, and are only fetched explicitly via pip arguments, or by URL directly as my package maintenance scripts do.
